result.execSummary:
The defendant Maurice D Jones was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Failure to Support Child (120 Days+), a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 948.22(2).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Maurice D Jones in court with attorney Christina E. Balistreri.  Edward OBrien appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Deputy court clerk:  vk  Parties have reached a resolution in this matter.
Plea hearing proceeded. Negotiations placed on the record and confirmed by defense counsel and defendant.
As to Count 1:  
Defendant changes his/her plea to GUILTY. Defendant was advised of constitutional rights and maximum penalties, waived all rights, plead GUILTY and was examined as to the plea.  Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights and Addendum received and filed.  Parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis for the plea.  Defendant further advised that if he/she is not a US citizen deportation is possible.  Court found defendant guilty as charged in the Information and ordered entry of Judgment of Conviction. Pursuant to Wisconsin Statutes section 973.176, the Court advised defendant that as a convicted felon he/she may never possess a firearm, ammunition or body armor. Court advised defendant that his/her voting rights are suspended, and may not vote in any election until his/her civil rights are restored.
As to Counts 2 & 3:  Pursuant to plea negotiations and on motion of State, Court ordered counts dismissed and read in.
State has complied with victim notification.  Sentencing hearing proceeded.  Statements made as to sentencing. Additonal statement by:  Anquiatte C

AS TO COUNT 1: The Court sentenced the defendant to 360 days in the House of Correction with 33 days credit time served.  Court allows for huber.

The Court STAYED this sentence and placed the defendant on probation for a period of 2 YEARS.  

Court orders the following conditions of probation: 
- AODA assessment and any recommended treatments
- absolute sobriety with random testing
- maintain work 

Court orders defendant to pay:
- child support arrears of $4187.83
- extraditon charges from the state of New York of $181.14
- child support obligation
  
Defendant shall provide a DNA sample for the Data Bank and pay all appropriate costs.

Court ordered defendant to pay mandatory court costs, surcharges, child support and extradition costs by the end of probation to convert to a civil judgment.  If defendant does not meet his child support obligations at the end of probation Court informed the defendant of possible additional contempt charges and commitments.   

Court advised defendant that as a convicted felon he may never possess a firearm, body armor or ammunition.  Court advised defendant that his voting rights are suspended and he may not vote in any election until his civil rights are restored.
